   "source": [
    "## Part 1a: Real Life Examples (2 points)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Understanding Causal Relationships in Economics\n",
    "\n",
    "In causal inference, we distinguish between different types of variables based on their relationships in a causal graph (DAG - Directed Acyclic Graph). Understanding these relationships is crucial for proper econometric identification and avoiding spurious correlations. Below, we provide three fundamental concepts with detailed economic examples.\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 1. Confounder: The Problem of Omitted Variable Bias\n",
    "\n",
    "**Theoretical Definition**: A confounder is a variable that causally influences both the treatment variable (X) and the outcome variable (Y). If not properly controlled for, confounders create spurious correlations between X and Y, leading to biased estimates of the causal effect.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Formulation**: If Z is a confounder, then:\n",
    "- Z → X (confounder affects treatment)\n",
    "- Z → Y (confounder affects outcome)  \n",
    "- X → Y (direct causal effect of interest)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Economic Example: Education Returns and Ability**\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the classic question in labor economics: What is the causal effect of education on earnings?\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Treatment (X)**: Years of Education\n",
    "- **Outcome (Y)**: Annual Earnings (log wages)\n",
    "- **Confounder (Z)**: Innate Ability (cognitive skills, motivation, family background)\n",
    "\n",
    "**The Confounding Problem**:\n",
    "1. **Ability → Education**: Higher ability individuals are more likely to pursue higher education (they face lower costs of learning and higher returns)\n",
    "2. **Ability → Earnings**: Higher ability individuals earn more regardless of education level\n",
    "3. **Education → Earnings**: Education itself may have a causal effect on earnings through skill development\n",
    "\n",
    "**Economic Implication**: Without controlling for ability, the observed correlation between education and earnings will overestimate the true causal effect of education, conflating the direct effect of schooling with the indirect effect through ability selection.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Policy Relevance**: This distinction is crucial for education policy - if most of the education-earnings correlation is due to ability sorting rather than skill development, then expanding access to education may have smaller effects on inequality than naive estimates suggest.\""
   ]
  },
