    "## Part 1b: Simpson's Paradox (2 points)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Understanding Simpson's Paradox in Economic Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "**Theoretical Foundation**: Simpson's Paradox occurs when a statistical relationship observed in aggregated data reverses or disappears when the data is partitioned into subgroups. This phenomenon highlights the critical importance of controlling for confounding variables and the dangers of ecological inference.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Condition**: For variables X, Y, and confounding variable Z:\n",
    "- Within each group (Z=z): Corr(X,Y|Z=z) has the same sign\n",
    "- In combined data: Corr(X,Y) has the opposite sign or no correlation\n",
    "- This occurs when Z is strongly associated with both X and Y, but in different directions\n",
    "\n",
    "**Economic Relevance**: Simpson's Paradox is pervasive in economic data due to heterogeneity across:\n",
    "- Time periods (business cycles, policy regimes)\n",
    "- Geographic regions (developed vs. developing countries)\n",
    "- Demographic groups (age cohorts, education levels)\n",
    "- Market segments (industries, firm sizes)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Simulation Design**: We create a controlled example where:\n",
    "1. **Two distinct groups** represent different skill levels of workers\n",
    "2. **Within each group**: More training leads to higher productivity (positive relationship)\n",
    "3. **Across groups**: The relationship appears negative due to selection effects\n",
    "\n",
    "This simulates a common economic scenario where high-skill workers receive less training (because they need it less) but have higher baseline productivity.\""
   ]
  },
